The current date and time can be printed using the JavaScript date object. The date object is constructed by calling the Date constructor and passing it the current date and time. The date object has a number of methods that can be used to extract the current date and time, and these methods can be used to print the current date and time.

One way to print the current date and time is to use the date object's toString method. This method returns a string that represents the date and time in the format specified by the locale. To print the current date and time using the toString method, the following code can be used:

```
var date = new Date();
console.log(date.toString());
```

This code creates a new date object and logs its toString representation to the console. The toString representation of the date object will be in the format specified by the locale.

Another way to print the current date and time is to use the date object's getHours, getMinutes, and getSeconds methods. These methods return the hour, minute, and second components of the current date and time, respectively. To print the current date and time using these methods, the following code can be used:

```
var date = new Date();
console.log(date.getHours() + ":" + date.getMinutes() + ":" + date.getSeconds());
```

This code creates a new date object and logs the hour, minute, and second components of the current date and time to the console.
